"Here are the answers to the questions:\n\n***Question 1: \"How likely is it that Bond will escape from Le Chiffre?\"***\n1. Not very likely\n\nThe passage suggests that Bond is trapped and outnumbered, with two gunmen and Le Chiffre himself. Bond's attempts to defend himself have been thwarted, and he is being searched and disarmed. This makes it unlikely that he will escape.\n\n***Question 2: \"How suspenseful do you find this passage to be?\"***\n7. Extremely suspenseful\n\nThe passage is suspenseful because it sets up a tense and unexpected situation. Bond is enjoying a moment of triumph, but it is quickly turned on its head as he is ambushed by Le Chiffre and his men. The use of action verbs like \"burst\", \"leapt\", and \"twisted\" creates a sense of urgency and danger, and Bond's feelings of puniness and impotence add to the sense of tension and suspense."